    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Life After Cancer</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Josie Zeman letter agrees that cancer changes everyone who has to deal with disease, including Mayor Rudolph Giuliani (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Cancer changes you. Just ask anyone who has dealt with the diagnosis and treatment. Joyce Purnick (Metro Matters column, May 11) writes, ''Most people with treatable cancers want to continue with their pre-diagnosis lives, and do.'' What she didn't say is that we never approach life in the same way again.</p>
        <p>I wish Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani the best as he battles the disease.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Cancer changes you. Just ask anyone who has dealt with the diagnosis and treatment. Joyce Purnick (Metro Matters column, May 11) writes, ''Most people with treatable cancers want to continue with their pre-diagnosis lives, and do.'' What she didn't say is that we never approach life in the same way again.</p>
        <p>I wish Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani the best as he battles the disease.</p>
        <p>And I understand what he means when he says that his political career is not his first concern at this difficult time for him and all his loved ones.</p>
        <p>JOSIE ZEMAN  Hoboken, N.J., May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
